{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180804195751|853437050","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Michael_McCaul","to":"Michael McCaul"}],"pages":{"1132718":{"pageid":1132718,"ns":0,"title":"Michael McCaul","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-08-08T15:39:46Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Mike McCaul\n|image        = Michael McCaul official photo.jpg\n|office       = Chair of the [[United States House Committee on Homeland Security|House Homeland Security Committee]]\n|term_start   = January 3, 2013\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Peter T. King|Peter King]]\n|successor    = \n|state1       = [[Texas]]\n|district1    = {{ushr|TX|10|10th}}\n|term_start1  = January 3, 2005\n|term_end1    = \n|predecessor1 = [[Lloyd Doggett]]\n|successor1   = \n|birth_name   = Michael Thomas McCaul\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1962|1|14}}\n|birth_place  = [[Dallas]], [[Texas]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Linda Mays\n|children     = 5\n|education    = [[Trinity University (Texas)|Trinity University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[St. Mary's University, Texas]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n}}\n'''Michael Thomas McCaul Sr.''' (born January 14, 1962) is the  [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|TX|10}}, serving since 2005.  Since the beginning of the [[113th Congress]], he has been the [[Chairman]] of the [[United States House Committee on Homeland Security|House Committee on Homeland Security]].  He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. The district stretches from [[Austin, Texas|Austin]] to [[Houston, Texas|Houston]]. {{asof|2017}} he is the [[List of current members of the United States Congress by wealth|third-wealthiest member of Congress]].\n\n==Early life, education, and law career==\nMcCaul was born in [[Dallas]], Texas, the son of Frances Jane (Lott) and James Addington McCaul, Jr. He has English, Irish, and German ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/mccaul.htm|title=michael mccaul|work=ancestry.com}}</ref> He graduated from [[Jesuit College Preparatory School of Dallas]]. He earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in history from [[San Antonio]]'s [[Trinity University (Texas)|Trinity University]] in 1984 and his [[Juris Doctor]] from [[St. Mary's University, Texas|St. Mary's University]] in 1987. McCaul also completed the Senior Executive Fellowship at the [[Kennedy School of Government]] of [[Harvard University]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jesuitdallas.org/news/alumni/u-s-rep-michael-mccaul-80-named-jesuit-dallas-distinguished-alumnus/ |title=U.S. Rep. Michael McCaul \u201980 Named Jesuit Dallas Distinguished Alumnus |publisher=[[Jesuit College Preparatory School of Dallas|Jesuit Dallas News]] |date=October 16, 2014 |accessdate=September 8, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908153851/http://www.jesuitdallas.org/news/alumni/u-s-rep-michael-mccaul-80-named-jesuit-dallas-distinguished-alumnus/ |archive-date=September 8, 2017 |dead-url=yes |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nMcCaul worked as an attorney and a federal prosecutor before entering politics. He was the Chief of Counterterrorism and National Security for Texas's branch of the [[US Attorney]]'s office, and also worked under the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]]'s Public Integrity Section. After he left the USDOJ, McCaul took a position as a Deputy Attorney General in 1998 with the Texas Attorney General's Office and served in this capacity until 2002.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n{{update|section|2010|date=December 2016}}\nHe ran for the U.S. House of Representatives in 2004.  He won a crowded Republican primary in the newly created 10th District.  The district was thought to be so heavily Republican that no [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] candidate even filed, effectively handing the seat to McCaul.\n\nIn 2006 he defeated [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] candidate Ted Ankrum and former [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] presidential candidate [[Michael Badnarik]] with 55% of the vote. McCaul won re-election once again in 2008, against Democratic candidate [[Larry Joe Doherty]] and Libertarian candidate Matt Finkel<ref name=2008electionresults>{{cite news\n |accessdate = November 6, 2008\n |url        = http://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/nov04_141_state.htm\n |title      = State of Texas 2008 General Election Returns\n |date       = November 5, 2008\n |publisher  = [[Texas Secretary of State]]\n}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> by a 54 to 43 percent margin.\n\nIn 2010, he was re-elected to a fourth term with 76% of the vote against Democratic candidate Ted Ankrum (22%) and Libertarian candidate Jeremiah \"JP\" Perkins (1 percent).\n\nMcCaul won a seventh term in the House in the general election held on November 8, 2016. With 179,221 votes (57.3 percent), he defeated the Democrat Tawana W. Cadien, who polled 120,170 (38.4 percent). The Libertarian Bill Kelsey held another 13,209 votes (4.2 percent).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist319_state.htm|title=Election Results|date=November 8, 2016|publisher=Texas Secretary of State|accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Controversy===\n{{criticism section|date=December 2016}}\n\nIn August 2011 [[AlterNet]] reported that McCaul, along with [[John Culberson]] and [[Ted Poe]], was attempting to remove the right of deceased soldiers families to choose which prayers, if any, were to be read at a soldier's funeral.<ref name=rock/><ref name=alternet/> The three politicians were said to be attempting to impose [[Christianity|Christian]] ceremonies on the military funerals of everybody who has served in the military, regardless of whether or not the deceased was Christian and with or without the consent of the family of the deceased. The three stated their demands were a response to [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs|Veterans Affairs]] (VA) banning Christian prayers at military funerals; however, VA state this claim is \"blatantly false\" as VA respects families' \"rights to pray however they choose at our national cemeteries\".<ref name=rock>{{cite web |url=http://rockbeyondbelief.com/2011/08/05/tx-congressmen-to-force-christian-prayer-over-my-dead-body/ |title=TX Congressmen to force Christian prayer over my dead body. |author=Griffith, Justin |date=August 5, 2011 |work=rockbeyondbelief.com |publisher= |accessdate=September 6, 2011}}</ref><ref name=alternet>{{cite web |url=http://www.alternet.org/world/152143/texas_legislators_and_christian_groups_fight_to_insert_god_into_vets'_funerals_--_against_families'_wishes/?page=entire |title=Texas Legislators and Christian Groups Fight to Insert God Into Vets' Funerals \u2013 Against Families' Wishes |author=DiBrance, Alex |date=August 23, 2011 |work=[[AlterNet]] |publisher= |accessdate=September 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, McCaul said that he would trust [[Russia]] rather than the United States to account for [[Syria]]'s chemical weapons stockpile.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/politico-live/2013/09/michael-mccaul-put-russian-boots-on-the-ground-172657.html|title=McCaul: Put Russian boots on the ground in Syria|author=Andrea Drusch|work=[[Politico]]}}</ref> He did say that the monitoring and destruction of the chemical weapons in Syria would have to be overseen by an international commission of the United Nations, emphasizing that Putin and Russia have superior leverage over Syria to better accomplish the removal of WMD from the Syrian arsenal.\n\nOn November 30, 2016 McCaul appeared on [[Fox News]] with [[Bret Baier]] to discuss his possible nomination to head the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]] by president-elect [[Donald Trump]].  McCaul's interview was marred with controversy when Baier cited a ''[[Washington Times]]'' article quoting William Gheen of Americans for Legal Immigration PAC which said \"We certainly hope that Donald Trump would not reward a deceptive pro-amnesty lawmaker like Michael McCaul with a Cabinet position,\" said William Gheen, president of Americans for Legal Immigration PAC. \"That would be very disappointing to all of us that believed his campaign promises to secure our borders and deport millions of illegal immigrants under current U.S. laws.\"<ref name=FoxNews>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4w-QDEDtmTs |title=Rep. Michael McCaul Accuses Americans for Legal Immigration of Slander on Fox News . |author=Baier, Bret |date=November 30, 2016}}</ref><ref name=WashingtonTimes>{{cite web |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/nov/29/donald-trumps-candidate-for-homeland-security-mich/ |title=Border hawks riled after Trump meeting with Texas\u2019 McCaul for Homeland post. |author=Miller, S.A. |date=November 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\n[[File:U.S. Congressman Michael McCaul addressing cybersecurity at Rice University.jpg|thumb|Congressman McCaul addressing [[cybersecurity]] at [[Rice University]]]]\nOn December 11, 2013, McCaul introduced the [[National Cybersecurity and Critical Infrastructure Protection Act of 2013 (H.R. 3696; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would amend the [[Homeland Security Act of 2002]] to require the [[Secretary of the Department of Homeland Security]] (DHS) to conduct cybersecurity activities on behalf of the federal government and would codify the role of DHS in preventing and responding to cybersecurity incidents involving the [[Information Technology]] (IT) systems of federal civilian agencies and critical infrastructure in the United States.<ref name=cbo3696>{{cite web|title=CBO \u2013 H.R. 3696|url=http://www.cbo.gov/sites/default/files/cbofiles/attachments/hr3696.pdf|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=July 28, 2014}}</ref><ref name=3696sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3696 \u2013 Summary|url=https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/3696|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=July 28, 2014}}</ref> McCaul said that the bill was \"an important step toward addressing the cyber threat.\"<ref name=WaddellThinkAdvisor>{{cite web|last1=Waddell|first1=Melanie|title=House Panel Passes Cybersecurity Bills|url=http://www.thinkadvisor.com/2014/07/29/house-panel-passes-cybersecurity-bills|website=ThinkAdvisor.com|accessdate=July 29, 2014|date=July 29, 2014}}</ref> According to McCaul, the bill \"establishes a true partnership between DHS and the private sector to ensure the distribution of real-time cyber threat information in order to secure our nation in cyberspace without burdensome mandates or regulations.\"<ref name=\"WaddellThinkAdvisor\"/>\n\nIn a December 2, 2016 [[Fox News]] op-ed, McCaul declared his intention to support legislation, in line with president-elect [[Donald Trump]]'s proposals, to build a wall along the [[Mexico\u2013United States border]], to secure the border, and have [[Mexico]] and other [[Latin America]]n countries pay for these proposals.<ref>{{cite web | last1=McCaul | first1=Michael | title=Rep. McCaul: Yes, We Will Build a Wall, Put Mexico on a \"Payment Plan\" and Enforce the Law | url=http://www.foxnews.com/opinion/2016/12/02/rep-mccaul-yes-will-build-wall-put-mexico-on-payment-plan-and-enforce-law.html | date=December 2, 2016 | publisher=[[Fox News]] | accessdate=December 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n[[File:U.S. Congressman Michael McCaul led House of Representatives Committee on Homeland Security to visit ISAF Headquarters.jpg|thumb|Congressman McCaul led [[United States House Committee on Homeland Security|House of Representatives Committee on Homeland Security]] to visit [[ISAF]] Headquarters]]In December 2016, the [[Republican Conference of the United States House of Representatives|House Republican Conference]] voted to appoint McCaul for a third term as the chairman of the House Committee on Homeland Security Committee. The selection follows McCaul\u2019s recent publication of \"A National Strategy to Win the War Against Islamist Terror\", a compilation of more than 100 counterterrorism strategies and recommendations. McCaul says his approach to counterterrorism will aid in integrating the nation\u2019s homeland security policies into the digital age through the implementation of detailed screening of foreign visitors, including immigrants and refugees, by utilizing the latest technologies and intelligence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://homelandprepnews.com/government/20374-mccaul-elected-chair-house-homeland-security-committee-third-term/|title=McCaul elected to chair House Homeland Security Committee for third term|last=|first=|date=2016-12-06|work=|newspaper=Homeland Preparedness News|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-08|via=}}</ref>\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere|Subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere]] (Vice Chair)\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Homeland Security|Committee on Homeland Security]]''' (Chairman)\n* '''[[Republican Study Committee]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=Republican Study Committee|date=|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* Co-Chair of the Congressional High Tech Caucus \u2013 '''Founder'''\n* Co-Chair of the Childhood Cancer Caucus- '''Co-Founder'''\n* Co-Chair of the Congressional Cyber Security Caucus \u2013\n* Co-Chair of the Congressional Caucus on Sudan and South Sudan \n* Tuberculosis Elimination Caucus\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|format=|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=4 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMcCaul is married to Linda Mays McCaul. She is the daughter of [[Clear Channel Communications]] chairman [[Lowry Mays]] and sister of its CEO [[Mark Mays]]. In 2011, [[Roll Call (newspaper)|Roll Call]] named McCaul as one of the wealthiest members of the [[United States Congress]], surpassing then [[U.S. Senator]] [[John Kerry]] (D-MA). His [[net worth]] was estimated at $294 million, which is approximately 300% higher than it was in the previous year ($74 million).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rollcall.com/50richest/the-50-richest-members-of-congress-112th.html |title=The 50 Richest Members of Congress (2011) |date= |work=[[Roll Call]] |publisher= |accessdate=February 15, 2013}}</ref> In 2004, Roll Call estimated his net worth at just $12 million. His wealth increase was due to large monetary transfers from his wife's family.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cooper |first=Kent |url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/mccaul_leaps_top_50_richest_members_congress-208231-1.html?pos=hftxt |title=McCaul Leaps to Top of 50 Richest Members of Congress : Roll Call News |publisher=Rollcall.com |date=August 18, 2011 |accessdate=August 10, 2014}}</ref> The McCauls live in [[West Lake Hills, Texas]], a wealthy suburb of [[Austin, Texas]], with their children, daughters Caroline, Jewell, Avery, and Lauren, and a son, Michael.{{citation needed| date=November 2013}}.  McCaul is frequently in the top ten users of household water in the Austin area, and was the #1 consumer of household water in Austin for 2017.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/texas-politics/2018/07/27/grass-really-greener-austin-rep-michael-mccaul-used-water-resident| title=Michael McCaul, one of Congress' richest members, used more water in 2017 than any Austin resident| work=[[Dallas Morning News]]|accessdate=July 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of richest American politicians]]\n* ''[[Final Report of the Task Force on Combating Terrorist and Foreign Fighter Travel]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Portalbar|Dallas|Texas|Law|Politics}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://mccaul.house.gov/ Congressman Michael McCaul] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.michaelmccaul.com/ Michael McCaul for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Texas/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Michael_McCaul_%5BR-10%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|michaelmccaul}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=m001157 | votesmart=49210 | fec=H4TX10093 | congress=michael-mccaul/1804 }}<!--\nLinks formerly displayed via the CongLinks template:\n* [http://ballotpedia.org/Michael_McCaul Biography] at [[Ballotpedia]]\n* [http://www.nndb.com/people/222/000086961 Biography] at [[NNDB]]\n* [http://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/400654 Congressional profile] at [[GovTrack]]\n* [http://www.opencongress.org/people/show/400654 Congressional profile] at [[Participatory Politics Foundation|OpenCongress]]\n* [http://www.rollcall.com/members/19182.html Congressional profile] at ''[[Roll Call]]''\n* [http://www.politifact.com/personalities/michael-mccaul Fact-checking] at [[PolitiFact.com]]\n* [http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N00026460 Financial information (federal office)] at [[Center for Responsive Politics|OpenSecrets.org]]\n* [http://apps.washingtonp